Strong Priorities for Fragile States
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI - No country has been spared from the aftermath of COVID-19.
However, the world's most "fragile" states are facing a set of particularly complex issues.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already struggling with poverty, conflicts, corruption, and inadequate public administration.
Today, these factors leave these countries poorly equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What each country needs to get through the pandemic is precisely what's missing from fragile states: a state apparatus capable of developing and implementing an action plan, an effective police force to enforce the rules, social programs providing funding, supplies, and health services to treat infected people.
The state's lack of resources is immediately felt in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions in Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
The Mali has only three ventilators for the entire country.
An effective response also depends on trust in the state's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states hardly benefits from the population's consent.
In countries that are recovering from a conflict or struggling with endemic corruption, several people will be cautious about supporting the government, even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an indispensable component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families and the state should be able to collect tax revenues in order to help those who cannot.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not present enough to meet these needs.
Earlier in the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the demographic weight of the young and geographical distance.
However, from our point of view as co-presidents of the new Council on State Fragility, it had to be noted that this was not the case.
In the last few weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia and Yemen have all had infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries hit by the coronavirus first.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more important for fragile states. They will not only be the result of national lockdowns, but also of what happens abroad.
Trade with countries like China has dwindled, remittances from expats have plummeted, prices of basic goods and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are piling up.
Since fragile states rely on imports for the majority of their food, we talk more and more about "hunger" and even "famine".
We should now have understood that the problems of less wealthy countries are for the most part global problems, whether in the form of massive migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the underprivileged populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will only get worse.
That is why the Council on State Fragility has set as its absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges that these countries must face.
The council, composed of former global leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, and development agency presidents, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. It will aim to guide national and international policymakers on how fragile states will get through this crisis and tackle their broader and deeper problems.
Strong Priorities for Fragile States will rely on decentralization, adaptability, and the wise use of data.
For instance, it is widely proven that "targeted confinement" of local outbreaks is often more suitable than national confinement.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act quickly, before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency dissipates.
We propose five recommendations.
Firstly, access to social protection should be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will be synonymous with universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile phone networks should be leveraged to collect information on immediate needs and dispense regular small payments (although limited in duration).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which used to cultivate rice, has become increasingly reliant over the last few decades.
Generally speaking, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Local production initiatives of basic crops must be quickly deployed on a much broader scale.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production is launched, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by richer countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate for and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, fragile states' businesses need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved international financial institutions, the small businesses in less affluent countries are often neglected and face the negative consequences of broader objectives and rules (since it is easier to reach an objective by investing in large-scale projects in larger economies).
However, it is precisely these small businesses that need larger investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support the heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying foreign creditors or saving their population.
About $40 billion in bilateral development aid is expected to be repaid to private and public creditors this year alone by countries receiving such aid.
To prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to temporarily suspend non-accrued debt not only until next year but also until the end of the crisis.
Moreover, it is essential that all fragile states receive emergency funding to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions — particularly countries that do not normally have access to financing from the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund.
The COVID-19 will aggravate existing problems in all fragile states worldwide.
However, if the international community reacts promptly, we can mitigate the worst repercussions of the pandemic.
If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
